Betty Friedan, a pioneer of the feminist movement, founded NOW and advocated for the Equal Rights Amendment.
Her book ignited modern feminism, challenging societal norms.
Friedan's impact on women's rights was profound, though she later shifted focus to ageism.
Despite criticism, her work reshaped cultural perceptions.
Friedan's legacy lives on through her groundbreaking contributions.
The ongoing debate on motherhood reflects evolving societal expectations.
Feminist perspectives on family and gender roles continue to shape public discourse.
Friedan's influence endures, sparking vital conversations on equality and empowerment.
